d people with higher incomes (coefficient on earning ≥\$100 000, 12.3 percentage points; 95\% CI, 8.7 to 15.8 percentage points; P {\textless} .001). Knowledge of potential fomite spread was lower among African American respondents (-9.4 percentage points; 95\% CI, -13.1 to -5.7 percentage points; P {\textless} .001), Hispanic respondents (-4.8 percentage points; 95\% CI, -8.9 to -0.77 percentage points; P = .02), and people younger than 30 years (-10.3 percentage points; 95\% CI, -14.1 to -6.5 percentage points; P {\textless} .001). Similar gaps were found with respect to knowledge of COVID-19 symptoms and preventive behaviors. Conclusions and Relevance: In this survey study of US adults, there were gaps in reported incidence of COVID-19 and knowledge regarding its spread and symptoms and social distancing behavior. More effort is needed to increase accurate information and encourage appropriate behaviors among minority communities, men, and younger people.},
